@selvaganesang , there is no reason to restrict the length of the DDL string from my point of view as well. This change is to remove one of the fixed length buffer allocation instead use dynamic allocation. 
I will study the rest of the code here in subsequent fixes. @prashanth-vasudev is also refactoring this same file, so I would like to further fix others after his refactoringis done. This PR is submitted now, because in some other forks, same change already done, so this will help the code merging. And also required to get rid of the DDL core dump which we saw several times.

This PR is ready for merge. The only failures are compGeneral failures unrelated to this PR change.
2016-11-16 02:51:09  TEST023  ### FAIL (6 lines)     ###

@traflm Please go ahead and merge if needed because it avoids the core dump and fixes a memory leak in TM.
looks great to me, a big contribution. I will merge it since there are no more comments.
Thanks once again for this great contribution.

overall looks good to me. +1 from me.
There are two following tasks for this though, it is OK to finish them in following check-ins instead of this one:
1. Since this impact the document, please file a JIRA to track the task of update SQL Reference Manual about this new function.
2. Add some test case, so others will be better understanding how this works.

A new jira is created to track the task for updating documents.
TRAFODION-2360

@traflm As usually, user can use SHA2 function to generate a key when using AES_ENCRYPT. But now, the SHA2 function only support 256 bits .
I'd like to enhance it first and then update the both test case and the document.

Has anyone looked into what this means from a license perspective? There are usually strict regulations related to encryption so I'd like to know a bit more about the origins of this code, the licenses related to it, and whether there are export restrictions involved.

@gtapper Thanks for the reminder. I think it it a exemption for open source. 

MySQL also providers these encrypt algorithms. From the code level, I use OpenSSL lib.

However I found a doc in DOC, https://www.bis.doc.gov/index.php/forms-documents/pdfs/1441-encryption-webinar-transcript-2861771-introduction-to-encryption-export-controls/file

I am totally confused with the open source part. Maybe we need legal expert to review it.
GNU licenses are not supported by Apache.  Do we require binding in any code that had a GNU license?  If not, does the customer that builds Trafodion require any new software to be downloaded?

Good catch, Roberta.  The /usr/include/regex.h file on my system has a GNU license. 

I think it is okay to use g++ compiler as long as we're not distributing that code. We are pulling in regex functions from libc, but it is shared library we are not distributing even with convenience binaries. But this is just part of the libc system shared lib, which I think is a standard part of the linux OS. So I'm thinking this is okay.

Here is the ASF info on crypto code: https://www.apache.org/dev/crypto.html

--Steve

I agree with Steve, this is part of libc function. It is same thing as printf()/malloc() from my point of view. But Google's RE2 is BSD-License, so if needed, we can use RE2, but that involve a new third-party software, and need to do more work to setup dev env, and also the distribution will require Google's RE2 as a dependency as well. I am trying to avoid that.
